slides.title: Network of named entities and terms (Cortext)
slides.text:
This is the network visualisation of the actors and terms/themes that emerge from a computational analysis of the literature (corpus of texts from URLs/ actors' statements, including newsmedia).
The network highlights the presence of new actors in the controversy and provides an exploratory analysis of semantic connections among actors.

slides.title: UK politics cluster
slides.text: The cluster includes some of the main actors in British politics (UK Parliament, conservative and labour party, House of common...). There is a link with the Communication act, the  NSPCC children charity (an actor already known), and with the theme of online harassment.

slides.title: European policy cluster- 1
slides.text: Among the new actors emerged from the statements we find a number of EU  and international bodies (EU commission, EU Parliament, Eurojust, but also the Internet Governance Forum...). These are very big organisations, which are mentioned by the list of actors collected in Google.co.uk.

slides.title: European policy cluster - 2
slides.text: They are connected to the themes: terrorist response (Eurojust), E-Commerce directive (EU Commission), data protection and privacy (European Union). They are very connected to one of our already known actors: the European Digital Rights Initiative (EDRI), which confirms its role as European advocacy organisation.

slides.title: Data protection regulations
slides.text: This cluster gathers different initiatives in data protection regulation, in UK (Data protection act), in Germany (BDSG) and at the EU level (Data protection directive). Data protection regulations concerns data usage and collection from social media, and they have interesting connections to Children protection.

slides.title: UK Government initiatives
slides.text: This cluster revolves around the UK government Interactive service initiative which connects themes about children safety or general safety online (e.g. against sexual threats). The NGO Internet Watch Foundation is related to this cluster.

slides.title: Anti-Muslim cluster
slides.text:
One of the clearest themes that emerge from the documents is the "Anti-muslim" theme. It connects a number of issues related to anti-muslim reactions, online threats, radicalisation and social media.
The University of Birmingham appears among the actors related to this topic.

slides.title: Counter Violent Extremism cluster
slides.text: Another cluster revolves around the theme of reactions against extremism (e.g. counter-narratives strategies). Among the related actors we find know entities, such as Oxford University, but also new ones as the World Economic Forum (WEF).

slides.title: Terrorism cluster
slides.text: Among the new actors emerged from the texts we find terrorist groups such as Al-Quaeda and ISIS. They relate to terrorist strategies on social media and there is an interesting connection to Youtube.

slides.title: Facebook cluster
slides.text: The text highlight a very specific issues related to Facebook: its content moderation rules, identity violation and cyber harassment

slides.title: Fake news
slides.text: Fake news is a very interesting theme and node in the network, as it connects Facebook with traditional news media such as the BBC or the Times.

slides.title: Academic research on Social media cluster 1
slides.text: The network shows several connections to research related terms: e.g. Natural Language Processing (NLP), social network analysis, event detection...these clusters show some of the different ways employed in academia to study social media

slides.title: Academic research on Social media cluster 2
slides.text:
Again, the network shows several connections to research related terms: e.g. big data analysis and about specific elements of social media e.g. bots, Twitter accounts, and issues: e.g. extremism, Woolwich incident.
Also Cardiff University and the Cosmos platform emerge from the texts.

slides.title: Academic research on Social media cluster 3
slides.text: A whole cluster of actors and terms relate to academic works on Critical Discourse Analysis
